stem: Which of the following is a commonly used metric for establishing reliability of measurement within the context of a single-subject design?
choiceA: Internal consistency
choiceB: Test-retest reliability
choiceC: Interobserver agreement
choiceD: The generalizability coefficient
correctText: Interobserver agreement

stem: A school psychologist is working with a cultural broker to understand how to support a student who recently moved to the district from India. The school psychologist then shares the information from the cultural broker with the teachers to use in the classroom. Which of the following best describes the type of consultation being used?
choiceA: Consultee-centered
choiceB: Multicultural
choiceC: Problem-solving
choiceD: Indirect
correctText: Multicultural

stem: A school psychologist serves a population consisting primarily of non-White students, many of whom identify as Black and Hispanic American. The school psychologist approaches a more experienced colleague for advice. Which TWO of the following recommendations should be offered to the school psychologist?
choiceA: When using an interpreter in a family conference, direct statements and questions to the interpreter to increase the accuracy of the translation.
choiceB: Understand that stereotypes can prevent understanding of factors unique to individual students and their families.
choiceC: Be aware that individuals within a family often differ in the degree to which they identify with the majority culture.
choiceD: Set aside personal cultural beliefs and values in working with this population.
correctText: Understand that stereotypes can prevent understanding of factors unique to individual students and their families. | Be aware that individuals within a family often differ in the degree to which they identify with the majority culture.

stem: Which of the following is the best example of action research?
choiceA: Reviewing the results of an empirical research study to find out whether a reading intervention is effective
choiceB: Conducting an experimental study in the school to determine whether cognitive behavior techniques are effective in alleviating anxiety
choiceC: Assisting a teacher in implementing a math intervention to determine whether it improves a class's math computation ability
choiceD: Reading testimonials on a Web site for a writing intervention program and deciding to implement the program in the school
correctText: Assisting a teacher in implementing a math intervention to determine whether it improves a class's math computation ability

stem: Emily is a kindergarten student with a hearing impairment. She is experiencing difficulties in phonemic awareness and reading comprehension. Teacher of the Deaf (TOD) services have been recommended for Emily; however, the student support team director would prefer that a special education teacher provide these services. Which of the following is the most appropriate course of action to ensure that Emily's needs are met?
choiceA: Training the special education teacher to provide TOD services
choiceB: Proceeding with the director's recommendation that only special education teacher supports are warranted
choiceC: Insisting that Teacher of the Deaf services have been recommended and should be considered
choiceD: Consulting with the speech and language therapist to revise Emily's plan of services
correctText: Insisting that Teacher of the Deaf services have been recommended and should be considered

stem: Juan is a third-grade student whose primary language is Spanish. Juan's teacher has observed that he has difficulty understanding and following directions. The teacher reports concerns with his sentence structure and grammar. Juan is reportedly quiet and does not speak much within the school environment. Based on this information, which of the following is the most appropriate recommendation at this time?
choiceA: Retaining Juan so he can develop his English skills with native-speaking peers
choiceB: Considering English-language learner services or supports
choiceC: Providing individual pull-out services for English language arts to improve Juan's grammar
choiceD: Recommending small-group social skills training for Juan
correctText: Considering English-language learner services or supports

stem: Which THREE of the following does NASP suggest school psychologists do to combat implicit bias?
choiceA: Raise awareness of implicit bias by sharing research on the topic at faculty meetings
choiceB: Advocate hiring faculty from diverse cultural backgrounds to work in the district
choiceC: Take additional classes in multicultural psychology
choiceD: Only work with students from the same cultural background as themselves
correctText: Raise awareness of implicit bias by sharing research on the topic at faculty meetings | Advocate hiring faculty from diverse cultural backgrounds to work in the district | Continually be mindful of their own implicit biases when working with students and families

stem: Which THREE of the following are key components NASP considers necessary for developing threat-assessment policies in schools?
choiceA: Creating district-wide procedures
choiceB: Conducting a needs assessment at the district and school levels
choiceC: Creating a team of professionals from different disciplines to evaluate crisis response
choiceD: Interviewing parents and students regarding the district's school safety policy
correctText: Creating district-wide procedures | Creating a team of professionals from different disciplines to evaluate crisis response | Raising awareness of district policies on school safety and threat response

stem: A school psychologist is interested in research on grade retention and believes that reviewing a meta-analysis may be helpful. Which of the following studies best exemplifies a meta-analysis?
choiceA: Many studies related to grade retention were analyzed, and the overall effect size was calculated as a result of the synthesis of the research.
choiceB: A study was conducted that compared grade retention rates to student dropout rates in one school.
choiceC: A county researched the grade retention rates and compared the retention rates to the pass rate on the national state exam.
choiceD: A student examines the number of students who have been retained over the past ten years in one district and compares their performance to their overall final high school GPA.
correctText: Many studies related to grade retention were analyzed, and the overall effect size was calculated as a result of the synthesis of the research.

stem: Which of the following is an example of test sensitivity?
choiceA: Performance on the DIBELS reading fluency measure was found to correlate well with other established measures of reading fluency.
choiceB: Two different teachers complete the BASC-3 for the same student, and similar scores are found across most subscales between the two teachers.
choiceC: The WISC-V accurately predicts which students are likely to be diagnosed with a specific learning disability.
choiceD: The Woodcock-Johnson IV shows good consistency of results over multiple administrations across most subtests.
correctText: The WISC-V accurately predicts which students are likely to be diagnosed with a specific learning disability.

stem: Which of the following court cases focuses on the duty to warn and protect others who may be in danger when someone reports intent to harm?
choiceA: Tarasoff v. Regents of the University of California
choiceB: Mills v. Board of Education of the District of Columbia
choiceC: Larry P. v. Riles
choiceD: Lau v. Nichols
correctText: Tarasoff v. Regents of the University of California

stem: An elementary school recently implemented a new reading program with the goal of reducing referrals. Because this initiative is new for the teachers, the building principal has asked the school psychologist to assist with implementation of the program. Which of the following activities is most appropriate for the school psychologist to participate in when assisting the teachers?
choiceA: Coteaching lessons once weekly to observe the students in the classroom
choiceB: Conducting weekly observations of each classroom to determine if the teachers are correctly following the curriculum and reporting to the principal with information from the observation
choiceC: Taking over for the teacher when implementing the reading program to identify students who might need more individualized support
choiceD: Helping to develop a means of tracking the progress of students receiving the intervention program and assisting teachers with the data collection process
correctText: Helping to develop a means of tracking the progress of students receiving the intervention program and assisting teachers with the data collection process

stem: Which of the following is the first step in selecting an appropriate academic intervention?
choiceA: Selecting an appropriate evidence-based intervention
choiceB: Monitoring the student's performance
choiceC: Assessing the student's current level of functioning to identify the skill deficit
choiceD: Evaluating the effectiveness of the intervention
correctText: Assessing the student's current level of functioning to identify the skill deficit

stem: A school psychologist serving a rural school district has found that the district is resistant to using academic interventions. The district uses a curriculum that has not been updated for 15 years. The school psychologist has found that there are significant discrepancies between the achievement levels of students who attend the district schools and those who attend the nearby city schools. Which of the following is the best course of action for the school psychologist to begin addressing the discrepancies?
choiceA: Advocating with district leaders for an update to the curriculum based on the evidence that shows the discrepancies between districts
choiceB: Continuing to advocate with teachers for interventions that address specific student deficits and documenting results
choiceC: Meeting with families to discuss their children's educational deficits and providing at-home intervention activities to increase achievement
choiceD: Presenting to the school board on how the school psychologist can improve district outcomes through evaluating more students for special education
correctText: Advocating with district leaders for an update to the curriculum based on the evidence that shows the discrepancies between districts

stem: Which of the following is the best example of a functional behavior assessment (FBA)?
choiceA: Completing a cognitive and achievement assessment for the purpose of identifying a specific learning disability
choiceB: Analyzing data to identify academic difficulties that can be addressed with interventions
choiceC: Completing an observation and interview for the purpose of identifying the function of a student's problem behavior
choiceD: Completing a depression screening for the purpose of identifying mental health concerns
correctText: Completing an observation and interview for the purpose of identifying the function of a student's problem behavior

stem: Which of the following is an example of progress monitoring?
choiceA: Completing cognitive testing to identify intellectual ability
choiceB: Completing classroom observations of a student for the purpose of identifying the function of a behavior
choiceC: Completing reading curriculum-based measures weekly to identify reading growth
choiceD: Administering a universal reading screener to all students
correctText: Completing reading curriculum-based measures weekly to identify reading growth

stem: A school psychologist is working with an eighth-grade student who has been demonstrating depressive symptoms. When the student says that she has been thinking about suicide, the school psychologist should first
choiceA: immediately contact the student's parents or guardians
choiceB: ask the student if she has a plan for self-harm
choiceC: ask the student if she feels safe
choiceD: immediately contact a crisis center
correctText: ask the student if she has a plan for self-harm

stem: Which of the following describes a key difference between formative and summative assessments?
choiceA: Formative assessments occur at the end of instruction, while summative assessments occur during instruction.
choiceB: Formative assessments are used to guide instruction, while summative assessments are used to evaluate learning at the end of instruction.
choiceC: Formative assessments are graded, while summative assessments are not graded.
choiceD: Formative assessments are used to rank students, while summative assessments are not used for ranking.
correctText: Formative assessments are used to guide instruction, while summative assessments are used to evaluate learning at the end of instruction.

stem: A school psychologist has recently been hired to work at an elementary school. The principal informs the psychologist that over the past year, there has been an increase in behavior referrals for students on the playground and in the hallways. Which of the following steps should the school psychologist take first?
choiceA: Meet with classroom teachers to identify strategies they use for playground and hallway transitions
choiceB: Review the referral data to identify common problem behaviors and the locations where they occur most frequently
choiceC: Contact the district's behavior specialist to schedule professional development on positive behavior support strategies
choiceD: Present a plan to implement a schoolwide positive behavior intervention and support (PBIS) program
correctText: Review the referral data to identify common problem behaviors and the locations where they occur most frequently

stem: A school psychologist is working with Sarah, a tenth-grade student who has expressed frustration with her lack of progress in math class. She has said that she studies hard and does well on most of her homework but that she does poorly on tests. During the evaluation, the school psychologist notices that Sarah appears very anxious during testing. Which of the following would be the best first step for the school psychologist to take?
choiceA: Recommend that Sarah be provided with extended testing time on all math tests
choiceB: Teach Sarah strategies to help her manage her anxiety during tests
choiceC: Contact Sarah's parents to suggest she see a doctor about anxiety medication
choiceD: Suggest that Sarah's teacher allow her to take tests in a separate, quieter location
correctText: Teach Sarah strategies to help her manage her anxiety during tests

stem: A school psychologist is evaluating David, a fourth-grade student, for special education eligibility. Which of the following sources of data would be most important for the school psychologist to gather to determine whether David qualifies for special education services?
choiceA: Medical records, teacher interview, and behavior checklist
choiceB: Cognitive assessment, achievement assessment, and progress monitoring data
choiceC: Parent interview, classroom observation, and medical records
choiceD: Universal screening data, teacher interview, and parent interview
correctText: Cognitive assessment, achievement assessment, and progress monitoring data

stem: Which of the following is the best example of a Tier 2 intervention?
choiceA: A schoolwide positive behavior support program
choiceB: A small-group social skills intervention
choiceC: An individualized behavior intervention plan
choiceD: A universal reading curriculum
correctText: A small-group social skills intervention

stem: A school psychologist is leading a professional development session on evidence-based practices in education. Which of the following best describes an evidence-based practice?
choiceA: A practice that has been used for many years and is supported by experienced teachers
choiceB: A practice that has been shown by rigorous research to produce positive results
choiceC: A practice that was developed by experts in the field
choiceD: A practice that is mandated by state or federal law
correctText: A practice that has been shown by rigorous research to produce positive results

stem: Which of the following is NOT typically a role of the school psychologist in a problem-solving team meeting?
choiceA: Facilitating the meeting and keeping the team focused on the agenda
choiceB: Making the final decision about which interventions to implement
choiceC: Analyzing assessment data and sharing the results with the team
choiceD: Helping the team identify evidence-based interventions
correctText: Making the final decision about which interventions to implement

stem: A school psychologist administers an intelligence test to a student. The student earns a Full Scale IQ score of 85 with a 95% confidence interval of 80-90. Which of the following is the best interpretation of this result?
choiceA: The student's true IQ is 85.
choiceB: There is a 95% probability that the student's true IQ falls between 80 and 90.
choiceC: The student will always score between 80 and 90 on this test.
choiceD: The student's IQ score is significantly below average.
correctText: There is a 95% probability that the student's true IQ falls between 80 and 90.

stem: Which of the following is the best strategy for a school psychologist to use when building rapport with a student who is reluctant to participate in an evaluation?
choiceA: Explaining the consequences if the student refuses to participate
choiceB: Starting with less demanding tasks and gradually moving to more challenging tasks
choiceC: Having the student's teacher or parent present during the evaluation
choiceD: Rushing through the evaluation to minimize the student's discomfort
correctText: Starting with less demanding tasks and gradually moving to more challenging tasks

stem: A school psychologist is consulting with a teacher about a student who frequently calls out answers without raising his hand. Which of the following intervention strategies would most directly address this behavior?
choiceA: Providing the student with a fidget toy to keep his hands busy
choiceB: Moving the student's seat closer to the teacher
choiceC: Teaching the student to use a self-monitoring checklist
choiceD: Providing the student with more opportunities to respond appropriately
correctText: Teaching the student to use a self-monitoring checklist

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has been identified as having a specific learning disability in reading. Which of the following assessment approaches would be most appropriate to determine the student's instructional level?
choiceA: Administering a standardized achievement test
choiceB: Administering curriculum-based measurement probes
choiceC: Administering a standardized intelligence test
choiceD: Conducting a classroom observation
correctText: Administering curriculum-based measurement probes

stem: Which of the following best describes the purpose of a behavior intervention plan (BIP)?
choiceA: To document the frequency and severity of a student's problem behaviors
choiceB: To identify the consequences that will be applied when a student misbehaves
choiceC: To provide a comprehensive plan for addressing problem behaviors based on the function of the behavior
choiceD: To determine whether a student qualifies for special education services
correctText: To provide a comprehensive plan for addressing problem behaviors based on the function of the behavior

stem: A school psychologist is working with a third-grade student who has difficulty completing assignments independently. The teacher reports that the student frequently asks for help and does not begin tasks without prompting. Which of the following strategies would be most effective for increasing the student's independent work completion?
choiceA: Providing the student with extended time to complete assignments
choiceB: Having the student complete assignments in a resource room with adult support
choiceC: Teaching the student to use a self-instruction strategy to guide task completion
choiceD: Modifying assignments to reduce the number of problems
correctText: Teaching the student to use a self-instruction strategy to guide task completion

stem: Which of the following types of validity evidence is most directly assessed by examining the relationship between test scores and an external criterion?
choiceA: Content validity
choiceB: Construct validity
choiceC: Criterion-related validity
choiceD: Face validity
correctText: Criterion-related validity

stem: A school psychologist is evaluating a student who was recently adopted from another country. The student has limited English proficiency and has been in the United States for less than one year. Which of the following should the school psychologist consider most carefully when selecting assessment instruments?
choiceA: Choosing tests with strong reliability evidence
choiceB: Selecting tests that were normed on students from the student's country of origin
choiceC: Using nonverbal measures of cognitive ability
choiceD: Administering tests in the student's native language only
correctText: Using nonverbal measures of cognitive ability

stem: A school psychologist is presenting results of an evaluation to a student's parents. The psychologist should
choiceA: use technical jargon to demonstrate expertise
choiceB: focus only on the student's weaknesses to justify the need for services
choiceC: explain results in language that is easy for the parents to understand
choiceD: avoid discussing any results that might concern the parents
correctText: explain results in language that is easy for the parents to understand

stem: Which of the following is the most appropriate use of intelligence test scores in educational decision-making?
choiceA: To rank students by ability and track them into different educational programs
choiceB: To predict a student's potential for academic achievement and success in life
choiceC: To identify discrepancies between ability and achievement for eligibility determination
choiceD: To determine the specific academic interventions a student needs
correctText: To identify discrepancies between ability and achievement for eligibility determination

stem: A school psychologist is working with a middle school student who has been experiencing social difficulties. The student reports feeling lonely and having trouble making friends. Which of the following interventions would be most appropriate?
choiceA: Referring the student for individual counseling with an outside therapist
choiceB: Enrolling the student in a social skills group at school
choiceC: Suggesting the parents arrange more playdates for the student
choiceD: Recommending the student be placed in a smaller classroom setting
correctText: Enrolling the student in a social skills group at school

stem: Which of the following assessment tools would be most appropriate for identifying students who may be at risk for reading difficulties at the beginning of first grade?
choiceA: A standardized reading achievement test
choiceB: A phonemic awareness screening measure
choiceC: A comprehensive reading diagnostic assessment
choiceD: A reading interest inventory
correctText: A phonemic awareness screening measure

stem: A school psychologist is consulting with a teacher about a student who has been having difficulty staying on task during independent work time. The teacher has tried several strategies but has not seen improvement. Which of the following should the school psychologist recommend first?
choiceA: Referring the student for a comprehensive evaluation
choiceB: Collecting more detailed data on the specific behaviors and conditions
choiceC: Implementing a token economy system
choiceD: Recommending the student for placement in a more structured classroom
correctText: Collecting more detailed data on the specific behaviors and conditions

stem: Which of the following is a characteristic of a well-designed single-subject research study?
choiceA: Random assignment to treatment and control groups
choiceB: Large sample size
choiceC: Multiple measures of the target behavior over time
choiceD: Double-blind procedures
correctText: Multiple measures of the target behavior over time

stem: A school psychologist is reviewing the results of a standardized test. The test manual indicates that the test has a reliability coefficient of .95. Which of the following best describes what this means?
choiceA: The test measures what it claims to measure 95% of the time.
choiceB: Scores on this test are highly consistent and stable.
choiceC: 95% of students will score within the average range.
choiceD: The test predicts future performance with 95% accuracy.
correctText: Scores on this test are highly consistent and stable.

stem: According to NASP's Model for Comprehensive and Integrated School Psychological Services, which of the following is considered a foundational domain?
choiceA: Data-based decision making
choiceB: Consultation and collaboration
choiceC: Legal, ethical, and professional practice
choiceD: Interventions and instructional support
correctText: Legal, ethical, and professional practice

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has a history of aggressive behavior. The student recently made a statement suggesting he might hurt another student. Which of the following should the school psychologist do first?
choiceA: Contact the student's parents
choiceB: Report the statement to the school administration
choiceC: Conduct a threat assessment
choiceD: Document the statement and continue monitoring
correctText: Conduct a threat assessment

stem: Which of the following is the best example of a performance-based assessment?
choiceA: A multiple-choice test on math facts
choiceB: A written essay on a historical topic
choiceC: A standardized reading comprehension test
choiceD: A teacher rating scale of student behavior
correctText: A written essay on a historical topic

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has been diagnosed with ADHD. Which of the following classroom accommodations would be most likely to help the student stay focused during instruction?
choiceA: Reducing the amount of homework assigned
choiceB: Providing preferential seating near the teacher
choiceC: Allowing the student to retake tests until passing
choiceD: Excusing the student from group activities
correctText: Providing preferential seating near the teacher

stem: Which of the following best describes the concept of response to intervention (RTI)?
choiceA: A model for identifying students with disabilities based on IQ-achievement discrepancies
choiceB: A multi-tiered system for providing increasingly intensive interventions to struggling students
choiceC: A process for evaluating the effectiveness of special education programs
choiceD: A method for assessing student intelligence without standardized tests
correctText: A multi-tiered system for providing increasingly intensive interventions to struggling students

stem: A school psychologist is evaluating a student for possible autism spectrum disorder. Which of the following assessment approaches would be most appropriate?
choiceA: Administering only standardized cognitive and achievement tests
choiceB: Using multiple sources of information including observation, interviews, and rating scales
choiceC: Relying primarily on parent report of early developmental history
choiceD: Focusing exclusively on academic performance data
correctText: Using multiple sources of information including observation, interviews, and rating scales

stem: Which of the following is the most appropriate way for a school psychologist to respond when a parent requests that their child's evaluation report not be shared with the school?
choiceA: Agree to keep the report confidential from school staff
choiceB: Explain that the report will be shared only with team members who need the information
choiceC: Refuse to complete the evaluation
choiceD: Share the full report with all school staff
correctText: Explain that the report will be shared only with team members who need the information

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has anxiety. The student's teacher reports that the student frequently asks to leave class to go to the nurse's office. Which of the following is the most likely function of this behavior?
choiceA: Attention seeking
choiceB: Escape or avoidance
choiceC: Sensory stimulation
choiceD: Tangible reinforcement
correctText: Escape or avoidance

stem: Which of the following statistical concepts is most useful for understanding how much variability in a student's test scores is due to measurement error?
choiceA: Mean
choiceB: Standard deviation
choiceC: Standard error of measurement
choiceD: Correlation coefficient
correctText: Standard error of measurement

stem: A school psychologist is conducting a consultation with a teacher about a student's behavior. Which of the following consultation models emphasizes collaboration between the consultant and consultee?
choiceA: Expert consultation
choiceB: Behavioral consultation
choiceC: Mental health consultation
choiceD: Conjoint behavioral consultation
correctText: Conjoint behavioral consultation

stem: Which of the following is the best way for a school psychologist to ensure cultural responsiveness when conducting an evaluation?
choiceA: Using only nonverbal tests for all students from diverse backgrounds
choiceB: Considering the student's cultural and linguistic background when interpreting results
choiceC: Avoiding discussion of cultural factors to maintain objectivity
choiceD: Using tests that have been translated into the student's native language
correctText: Considering the student's cultural and linguistic background when interpreting results

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who exhibits oppositional behavior. The teacher reports that the student often refuses to follow directions and argues with adults. Which of the following interventions would be most effective as a first step?
choiceA: Implementing a punishment-based consequence system
choiceB: Providing clear expectations and positive reinforcement for compliance
choiceC: Removing the student from class when oppositional behavior occurs
choiceD: Referring the student for an outside mental health evaluation
correctText: Providing clear expectations and positive reinforcement for compliance

stem: Which of the following is a key characteristic of norm-referenced tests?
choiceA: They measure a student's mastery of specific content standards.
choiceB: They compare a student's performance to that of a representative sample.
choiceC: They assess a student's rate of progress over time.
choiceD: They are designed to be administered by classroom teachers.
correctText: They compare a student's performance to that of a representative sample.

stem: A school psychologist notices that a disproportionate number of students from one ethnic group are being referred for special education evaluation. Which of the following is the most appropriate first step to address this issue?
choiceA: Declining to evaluate students from that ethnic group
choiceB: Examining referral practices and data to identify potential sources of bias
choiceC: Recommending fewer students from that group for special education services
choiceD: Using only assessments developed for that specific ethnic group
correctText: Examining referral practices and data to identify potential sources of bias

stem: Which of the following best describes the difference between accommodations and modifications?
choiceA: Accommodations change what is taught; modifications change how it is taught.
choiceB: Accommodations change how a student learns or demonstrates learning; modifications change the learning expectations.
choiceC: Accommodations are only for students with disabilities; modifications are for all students.
choiceD: Accommodations are permanent; modifications are temporary.
correctText: Accommodations change how a student learns or demonstrates learning; modifications change the learning expectations.

stem: A school psychologist is working with a high school student who is planning for transition to postsecondary education. Which of the following assessment areas would be most important to address?
choiceA: Phonemic awareness
choiceB: Self-determination and self-advocacy skills
choiceC: Fine motor coordination
choiceD: Prereading skills
correctText: Self-determination and self-advocacy skills

stem: Which of the following is the most appropriate role for a school psychologist during a crisis response?
choiceA: Providing long-term individual therapy to affected students
choiceB: Offering immediate psychological first aid and support
choiceC: Conducting comprehensive mental health evaluations
choiceD: Assigning students to support groups based on diagnosis
correctText: Offering immediate psychological first aid and support

stem: A school psychologist is reviewing research on a reading intervention program. Which of the following research designs would provide the strongest evidence of the program's effectiveness?
choiceA: A case study of one student who improved after using the program
choiceB: A randomized controlled trial comparing students who used the program to those who did not
choiceC: A survey of teachers who used the program and reported satisfaction
choiceD: A comparison of test scores before and after program implementation without a control group
correctText: A randomized controlled trial comparing students who used the program to those who did not

stem: Which of the following cognitive processes is most directly assessed by measures of processing speed?
choiceA: The ability to hold information in mind while working with it
choiceB: The ability to quickly and efficiently perform simple cognitive tasks
choiceC: The ability to reason and solve novel problems
choiceD: The ability to retrieve information from long-term memory
correctText: The ability to quickly and efficiently perform simple cognitive tasks

stem: A school psychologist is conducting a counseling session with a student who is struggling with peer relationships. Which of the following approaches would be most consistent with a cognitive-behavioral perspective?
choiceA: Exploring the student's early childhood experiences
choiceB: Helping the student identify and challenge negative thoughts about peers
choiceC: Using play therapy techniques to help the student express feelings
choiceD: Focusing on the unconscious motivations behind the student's behavior
correctText: Helping the student identify and challenge negative thoughts about peers

stem: Which of the following is the most appropriate use of standardized test norms?
choiceA: To determine whether a student has mastered grade-level content standards
choiceB: To compare a student's performance to that of same-age or same-grade peers
choiceC: To measure a student's rate of improvement over time
choiceD: To identify specific skills that need remediation
correctText: To compare a student's performance to that of same-age or same-grade peers

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student whose parents are going through a divorce. The student has been having difficulty concentrating in class. Which of the following would be the most appropriate intervention?
choiceA: Referring the student for a comprehensive evaluation for attention problems
choiceB: Providing supportive counseling to help the student cope with the family changes
choiceC: Recommending that the student be placed in a smaller classroom
choiceD: Contacting the parents to recommend family therapy
correctText: Providing supportive counseling to help the student cope with the family changes

stem: Which of the following is a primary advantage of using curriculum-based measurement for progress monitoring?
choiceA: It provides detailed diagnostic information about specific skill deficits.
choiceB: It can be administered frequently without practice effects.
choiceC: It compares students to a national normative sample.
choiceD: It measures a comprehensive range of academic skills.
correctText: It can be administered frequently without practice effects.

stem: A school psychologist is asked to help a teacher who is struggling to manage a particularly challenging classroom. Which of the following consultation approaches would be most effective?
choiceA: Taking over the classroom for a day to demonstrate effective strategies
choiceB: Working collaboratively with the teacher to identify problems and develop solutions
choiceC: Providing the teacher with a list of research-based strategies to implement
choiceD: Observing the classroom and reporting findings to the principal
correctText: Working collaboratively with the teacher to identify problems and develop solutions

stem: Which of the following assessment tools would be most appropriate for measuring a student's executive functioning skills?
choiceA: A standardized achievement test
choiceB: A behavior rating scale designed to assess executive function
choiceC: A projective personality assessment
choiceD: A universal reading screener
correctText: A behavior rating scale designed to assess executive function

stem: A school psychologist is interpreting results from a cognitive assessment. The student's Verbal Comprehension Index score is significantly higher than the Perceptual Reasoning Index score. Which of the following interpretations is most appropriate?
choiceA: The student has a learning disability.
choiceB: The Full Scale IQ is a valid representation of the student's overall ability.
choiceC: The student shows a pattern of relative strengths and weaknesses that should be considered in educational planning.
choiceD: The student should be referred for further evaluation of nonverbal learning disability.
correctText: The student shows a pattern of relative strengths and weaknesses that should be considered in educational planning.

stem: Which of the following is the best example of applied behavior analysis?
choiceA: Using psychoanalytic techniques to understand a student's behavior
choiceB: Implementing systematic reinforcement procedures to change behavior
choiceC: Prescribing medication to address behavioral symptoms
choiceD: Using projective techniques to assess personality
correctText: Implementing systematic reinforcement procedures to change behavior

stem: A school psychologist is conducting an evaluation of a student referred for possible specific learning disability. Which of the following would be most important to rule out before identifying the student as having SLD?
choiceA: Emotional disturbance
choiceB: Lack of appropriate instruction
choiceC: Autism spectrum disorder
choiceD: Other health impairment
correctText: Lack of appropriate instruction

stem: Which of the following best describes the purpose of universal screening?
choiceA: To diagnose specific disabilities in students
choiceB: To identify students who may need additional support or intervention
choiceC: To determine eligibility for special education services
choiceD: To evaluate the effectiveness of classroom instruction
correctText: To identify students who may need additional support or intervention

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has been identified as gifted. The student reports feeling bored and unchallenged in class. Which of the following would be the most appropriate recommendation?
choiceA: Placing the student in a self-contained classroom for students with disabilities
choiceB: Providing enrichment activities and acceleration opportunities
choiceC: Recommending that the student skip two grade levels
choiceD: Suggesting the parents find educational opportunities outside of school
correctText: Providing enrichment activities and acceleration opportunities

stem: Which of the following is the most appropriate use of dynamic assessment?
choiceA: To compare a student's performance to national norms
choiceB: To assess a student's learning potential and responsiveness to instruction
choiceC: To diagnose specific learning disabilities
choiceD: To measure achievement in specific academic content areas
correctText: To assess a student's learning potential and responsiveness to instruction

stem: A school psychologist is meeting with a parent who is concerned about their child's progress. The parent asks the school psychologist to explain what a percentile rank means. Which of the following explanations would be most accurate and helpful?
choiceA: It shows the percentage of questions your child answered correctly.
choiceB: It shows how your child's performance compares to other students of the same age or grade.
choiceC: It predicts your child's future academic success.
choiceD: It shows the percentage of content your child has mastered.
correctText: It shows how your child's performance compares to other students of the same age or grade.

stem: Which of the following is the best strategy for a school psychologist to use when working with resistant parents who do not want their child evaluated?
choiceA: Proceeding with the evaluation since it is in the child's best interest
choiceB: Building rapport and explaining the potential benefits of the evaluation
choiceC: Having the principal contact the parents to require participation
choiceD: Documenting the refusal and closing the case
correctText: Building rapport and explaining the potential benefits of the evaluation

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who exhibits anxiety in test-taking situations. The student's teacher asks the school psychologist to provide extended time on tests as an accommodation. Which of the following should the school psychologist do?
choiceA: Recommend extended time for all students in the class to be fair
choiceB: Gather data to determine whether extended time is an appropriate accommodation for this student
choiceC: Refuse to provide any accommodations until a formal evaluation is completed
choiceD: Automatically approve the extended time request since the teacher made the request
correctText: Gather data to determine whether extended time is an appropriate accommodation for this student

stem: Which of the following is a key principle of positive behavior support?
choiceA: Punishment is the most effective way to change behavior.
choiceB: Behavior should be addressed by changing the environment and teaching new skills.
choiceC: Problem behavior indicates that a student needs a more restrictive placement.
choiceD: Behavior change occurs best through external control systems.
correctText: Behavior should be addressed by changing the environment and teaching new skills.

stem: A school psychologist is conducting a group counseling session for students who have experienced recent loss. Which of the following is the most important consideration when forming the group?
choiceA: Ensuring all students in the group have the same type of loss
choiceB: Including students who are at similar developmental levels
choiceC: Requiring parent permission for participation
choiceD: Limiting the group to no more than three students
correctText: Requiring parent permission for participation

stem: Which of the following best describes the difference between intelligence and achievement?
choiceA: Intelligence measures what a student knows; achievement measures learning potential.
choiceB: Intelligence measures reasoning and problem-solving ability; achievement measures learned knowledge and skills.
choiceC: Intelligence is fixed; achievement changes over time.
choiceD: Intelligence tests are norm-referenced; achievement tests are criterion-referenced.
correctText: Intelligence measures reasoning and problem-solving ability; achievement measures learned knowledge and skills.

stem: A school psychologist is developing a behavior intervention plan for a student who engages in frequent off-task behavior during independent work time. Functional behavior assessment data suggest the behavior is maintained by escape from task demands. Which of the following interventions would be most appropriate?
choiceA: Providing the student with attention when on-task
choiceB: Allowing the student to take breaks contingent on work completion
choiceC: Moving the student to a quiet area when off-task
choiceD: Ignoring the off-task behavior
correctText: Allowing the student to take breaks contingent on work completion

stem: Which of the following is the most appropriate action for a school psychologist to take when a colleague discloses unethical behavior?
choiceA: Ignoring the information since it does not directly affect the school psychologist's work
choiceB: Attempting to address the issue informally with the colleague first
choiceC: Immediately reporting the colleague to the state licensing board
choiceD: Documenting the disclosure but taking no further action
correctText: Attempting to address the issue informally with the colleague first

stem: A school psychologist is evaluating a student who may have an intellectual disability. Which of the following criteria must be met for this diagnosis?
choiceA: Significant limitations in intellectual functioning only
choiceB: Significant limitations in adaptive behavior only
choiceC: Significant limitations in both intellectual functioning and adaptive behavior with onset during the developmental period
choiceD: IQ score below 70 regardless of adaptive functioning
correctText: Significant limitations in both intellectual functioning and adaptive behavior with onset during the developmental period

stem: Which of the following is a key characteristic of criterion-referenced tests?
choiceA: They compare a student's performance to a normative sample.
choiceB: They assess mastery of specific skills or content standards.
choiceC: They are typically administered once per year.
choiceD: They require standardized administration procedures.
correctText: They assess mastery of specific skills or content standards.

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has been bullied. Which of the following is the most appropriate intervention approach?
choiceA: Telling the student to ignore the bullying
choiceB: Working with both the student who was bullied and those who engaged in bullying
choiceC: Moving the student who was bullied to a different classroom
choiceD: Recommending the student who was bullied receive training in self-defense
correctText: Working with both the student who was bullied and those who engaged in bullying

stem: Which of the following cognitive processes is most directly related to a student's ability to solve novel problems?
choiceA: Processing speed
choiceB: Working memory
choiceC: Fluid reasoning
choiceD: Long-term retrieval
correctText: Fluid reasoning

stem: A school psychologist is presenting at a staff meeting on the topic of trauma-informed practices. Which of the following is a key principle of trauma-informed care?
choiceA: All students who have experienced trauma need individual therapy
choiceB: Creating safe, predictable environments that support emotional regulation
choiceC: Requiring students to discuss their traumatic experiences in group settings
choiceD: Using punishment-based approaches to address trauma-related behaviors
correctText: Creating safe, predictable environments that support emotional regulation

stem: Which of the following best describes a Type I error in research?
choiceA: Concluding there is no effect when there actually is one
choiceB: Concluding there is an effect when there actually is not one
choiceC: Using an inappropriate statistical test
choiceD: Having too small a sample size
correctText: Concluding there is an effect when there actually is not one

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has autism spectrum disorder. The student becomes very upset when routines are changed. Which of the following strategies would be most helpful?
choiceA: Eliminating all changes to the student's routine
choiceB: Providing advance notice and visual supports before changes occur
choiceC: Ignoring the student's distress until it passes
choiceD: Requiring the student to adapt to changes without support
correctText: Providing advance notice and visual supports before changes occur

stem: Which of the following is the primary purpose of an IEP progress report?
choiceA: To determine whether the student still qualifies for special education
choiceB: To document the student's progress toward annual IEP goals
choiceC: To compare the student's performance to that of peers
choiceD: To identify new goals for the upcoming year
correctText: To document the student's progress toward annual IEP goals

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has selective mutism. Which of the following interventions would be most appropriate?
choiceA: Requiring the student to speak in all situations
choiceB: Using a graduated exposure approach to increase verbal communication
choiceC: Allowing the student to communicate only in writing
choiceD: Removing the student from social situations
correctText: Using a graduated exposure approach to increase verbal communication

stem: Which of the following is the most important factor in determining whether an intervention should be continued?
choiceA: Whether the teacher likes implementing the intervention
choiceB: Whether the student's progress monitoring data show improvement
choiceC: Whether the intervention is research-based
choiceD: Whether the intervention was recommended by an outside expert
correctText: Whether the student's progress monitoring data show improvement

stem: A school psychologist is facilitating a problem-solving meeting. The team has identified that a student is struggling with reading fluency. Which of the following should the team do next?
choiceA: Select an intervention from a list of evidence-based programs
choiceB: Analyze the student's specific reading error patterns
choiceC: Refer the student for special education evaluation
choiceD: Recommend the student for retention
correctText: Analyze the student's specific reading error patterns

stem: Which of the following best describes the principle of least restrictive environment (LRE)?
choiceA: Students with disabilities should receive all services in the general education classroom.
choiceB: Students with disabilities should be educated with nondisabled peers to the maximum extent appropriate.
choiceC: Students with disabilities should receive services in specialized settings.
choiceD: Students with disabilities should be grouped together for instruction.
correctText: Students with disabilities should be educated with nondisabled peers to the maximum extent appropriate.

stem: A school psychologist administers an achievement test to a student. The student earns a standard score of 85 in reading comprehension. This score falls in which range?
choiceA: Below average
choiceB: Average
choiceC: Above average
choiceD: Significantly below average
correctText: Average

stem: Which of the following is the best example of a social validity measure?
choiceA: Measuring how many times a behavior occurs
choiceB: Surveying teachers about whether they find an intervention acceptable and useful
choiceC: Calculating effect sizes from research studies
choiceD: Administering a standardized behavior rating scale
correctText: Surveying teachers about whether they find an intervention acceptable and useful

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has a specific learning disability in math. The student struggles with math fact fluency but understands mathematical concepts. Which of the following accommodations would be most appropriate?
choiceA: Reducing the number of math problems assigned
choiceB: Allowing the student to use a calculator for computation
choiceC: Providing the student with a modified math curriculum
choiceD: Excusing the student from math class
correctText: Allowing the student to use a calculator for computation

stem: Which of the following is a primary characteristic of effective progress monitoring?
choiceA: It is administered at the beginning and end of the school year.
choiceB: It is administered frequently using standardized procedures.
choiceC: It compares student performance to grade-level expectations.
choiceD: It provides detailed diagnostic information about specific skills.
correctText: It is administered frequently using standardized procedures.

stem: A school psychologist is reviewing data from a schoolwide positive behavior intervention and support (PBIS) program. Which of the following metrics would be most useful for evaluating program effectiveness?
choiceA: Number of students referred for special education
choiceB: Office discipline referrals and suspensions
choiceC: Scores on standardized achievement tests
choiceD: Teacher satisfaction surveys
correctText: Office discipline referrals and suspensions

stem: Which of the following is the most appropriate response when a student discloses abuse to a school psychologist?
choiceA: Promising the student that the information will be kept confidential
choiceB: Reporting the disclosure to child protective services as mandated by law
choiceC: Investigating the allegation before making any report
choiceD: Asking the student to write a detailed account of what happened
correctText: Reporting the disclosure to child protective services as mandated by law

stem: A school psychologist is consulting with a teacher who reports that a student frequently engages in attention-seeking behavior. Which of the following interventions would be most appropriate?
choiceA: Ignoring all of the student's behavior
choiceB: Providing attention for appropriate behavior and minimizing attention for inappropriate behavior
choiceC: Sending the student to the office when attention-seeking behavior occurs
choiceD: Providing more individual attention to prevent the behavior
correctText: Providing attention for appropriate behavior and minimizing attention for inappropriate behavior

stem: Which of the following assessment approaches would be most appropriate for evaluating a preschool child's development?
choiceA: Standardized intelligence testing with verbal and nonverbal subtests
choiceB: Developmental screening followed by comprehensive evaluation if concerns are identified
choiceC: Academic achievement testing
choiceD: Self-report questionnaires about social-emotional functioning
correctText: Developmental screening followed by comprehensive evaluation if concerns are identified

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has experienced a traumatic event. The student has been having nightmares and flashbacks. Which of the following interventions would be most appropriate?
choiceA: Requiring the student to describe the traumatic event in detail
choiceB: Referring the student to a trauma-focused mental health specialist
choiceC: Telling the student to try not to think about what happened
choiceD: Focusing only on academic performance
correctText: Referring the student to a trauma-focused mental health specialist

stem: Which of the following is a key ethical principle that guides school psychologists' practice?
choiceA: Maximizing assessment revenue for the school district
choiceB: Acting in the best interests of children
choiceC: Prioritizing the preferences of teachers over parents
choiceD: Maintaining strict confidentiality in all circumstances
correctText: Acting in the best interests of children

stem: A school psychologist is developing an intervention for a student who has difficulty organizing homework assignments. Which of the following would be the most effective strategy?
choiceA: Having the teacher reduce the amount of homework assigned
choiceB: Teaching the student to use a planner and organizational system
choiceC: Requiring the student's parents to check homework each night
choiceD: Having the student complete all homework at school
correctText: Teaching the student to use a planner and organizational system

stem: Which of the following best describes the purpose of a systematic review?
choiceA: To provide an expert opinion on a topic
choiceB: To synthesize research evidence using explicit and reproducible methods
choiceC: To describe findings from a single research study
choiceD: To generate new research hypotheses
correctText: To synthesize research evidence using explicit and reproducible methods

stem: A school psychologist is working with a family from a collectivist culture. Which of the following would be most important to consider?
choiceA: Communicating directly with the student without involving the family
choiceB: Including extended family members in discussions about the student's education
choiceC: Expecting the student to advocate independently for their needs
choiceD: Focusing exclusively on individual student outcomes
correctText: Including extended family members in discussions about the student's education

stem: Which of the following is the best way to establish a positive working relationship with a resistant teacher during consultation?
choiceA: Emphasizing the school psychologist's expertise
choiceB: Listening to the teacher's concerns and acknowledging their perspective
choiceC: Telling the teacher what strategies must be implemented
choiceD: Suggesting that the principal mandate the teacher's participation
correctText: Listening to the teacher's concerns and acknowledging their perspective

stem: A school psychologist is interpreting the results of a behavior rating scale. Two teachers rated the same student, and their ratings were significantly different. Which of the following is the most appropriate interpretation?
choiceA: One of the teachers is incorrect.
choiceB: The behavior may vary across settings or contexts.
choiceC: The rating scale is not reliable.
choiceD: The student has multiple behavior disorders.
correctText: The behavior may vary across settings or contexts.

stem: Which of the following is a primary advantage of using multiple regression in research?
choiceA: It determines causation between variables.
choiceB: It allows examination of the relationship between one outcome and multiple predictors.
choiceC: It eliminates the need for control groups.
choiceD: It is easier to compute than correlation.
correctText: It allows examination of the relationship between one outcome and multiple predictors.

stem: A school psychologist is asked to help develop a school crisis response plan. Which of the following should be included?
choiceA: A plan that addresses only natural disasters
choiceB: Comprehensive procedures for various types of crises including communication and recovery
choiceC: A plan developed solely by the school psychologist
choiceD: A plan that focuses only on immediate response, not prevention or recovery
correctText: Comprehensive procedures for various types of crises including communication and recovery

stem: Which of the following is the most important consideration when selecting an academic intervention for a student?
choiceA: Whether the intervention is new and innovative
choiceB: Whether research evidence supports the intervention's effectiveness for the student's identified needs
choiceC: Whether the intervention is recommended by other school psychologists
choiceD: Whether the intervention requires minimal teacher training
correctText: Whether research evidence supports the intervention's effectiveness for the student's identified needs

stem: A school psychologist notices that their own cultural background differs significantly from that of a student they are evaluating. Which of the following is the most appropriate action?
choiceA: Asking another psychologist with a similar background to the student to conduct the evaluation
choiceB: Proceeding with the evaluation while being mindful of potential cultural influences on assessment
choiceC: Using only tests developed in the student's culture of origin
choiceD: Ignoring cultural differences to maintain objectivity
correctText: Proceeding with the evaluation while being mindful of potential cultural influences on assessment

stem: Which of the following is the best example of interrater reliability?
choiceA: A student receives similar scores when tested on two different days.
choiceB: Two observers recording the same behavior at the same time obtain similar data.
choiceC: A test measures what it is supposed to measure.
choiceD: Different items on a test measure the same construct.
correctText: Two observers recording the same behavior at the same time obtain similar data.

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student who has test anxiety. Which of the following techniques would be most appropriate to teach the student?
choiceA: Avoiding tests whenever possible
choiceB: Relaxation and positive self-talk strategies
choiceC: Requesting that tests be given orally instead
choiceD: Having a parent present during testing
correctText: Relaxation and positive self-talk strategies

stem: Which of the following is a key component of effective parent-school communication?
choiceA: Limiting contact to formal meetings only
choiceB: Using jargon to demonstrate professional expertise
choiceC: Establishing regular, two-way communication channels
choiceD: Communicating primarily through written reports
correctText: Establishing regular, two-way communication channels

stem: A school psychologist is reviewing research on an intervention program. The study reports a statistically significant effect with p < .05. Which of the following is the most appropriate interpretation?
choiceA: The intervention will work for 95% of students.
choiceB: There is less than a 5% probability that the observed effect occurred by chance.
choiceC: The intervention has a large practical effect.
choiceD: The results are clinically meaningful.
correctText: There is less than a 5% probability that the observed effect occurred by chance.

stem: Which of the following is the most appropriate way for a school psychologist to address a situation where they realize they may have made an error during an evaluation?
choiceA: Ignoring the error if it seems minor
choiceB: Acknowledging the error and taking steps to correct it
choiceC: Completing the evaluation without mentioning the error
choiceD: Waiting to see if anyone notices the error
correctText: Acknowledging the error and taking steps to correct it

stem: A school psychologist is working with a student diagnosed with depression. Which of the following school-based interventions would be most appropriate?
choiceA: Prescribing antidepressant medication
choiceB: Implementing cognitive-behavioral strategies and monitoring mood
choiceC: Reducing academic expectations
choiceD: Isolating the student from peers
correctText: Implementing cognitive-behavioral strategies and monitoring mood

stem: Which of the following is the best way for a school psychologist to stay current with evidence-based practices?
choiceA: Relying solely on information from colleagues
choiceB: Engaging in ongoing professional development and reading peer-reviewed research
choiceC: Using the same assessment and intervention approaches learned in graduate school
choiceD: Attending only state-mandated training sessions
correctText: Engaging in ongoing professional development and reading peer-reviewed research

stem: A school psychologist is evaluating a student for possible emotional disturbance. Which of the following characteristics must be present for this classification under IDEA?
choiceA: An inability to learn that cannot be explained by intellectual, sensory, or health factors
choiceB: A medical diagnosis of a mental health disorder
choiceC: Aggressive behavior toward peers and adults
choiceD: Failure to respond to behavioral interventions
correctText: An inability to learn that cannot be explained by intellectual, sensory, or health factors

stem: Which of the following best describes the purpose of a manifestation determination review?
choiceA: To determine whether a student qualifies for special education
choiceB: To determine whether a student's behavior was caused by or related to their disability
choiceC: To develop a behavior intervention plan
choiceD: To decide whether a student should be suspended
correctText: To determine whether a student's behavior was caused by or related to their disability

stem: A school psychologist is working with a teacher who wants to implement a token economy in the classroom. Which of the following is the most important consideration?
choiceA: Ensuring all students receive the same number of tokens
choiceB: Defining target behaviors clearly and delivering tokens consistently
choiceC: Using tokens that have monetary value
choiceD: Implementing the system for at least one full school year
correctText: Defining target behaviors clearly and delivering tokens consistently

stem: Which of the following is the most appropriate response when a school psychologist identifies a potential conflict of interest in providing services to a student?
choiceA: Proceeding with services but documenting the conflict
choiceB: Disclosing the conflict and, if necessary, referring to another professional
choiceC: Ignoring the conflict if it does not seem serious
choiceD: Letting the parents decide how to handle the conflict
correctText: Disclosing the conflict and, if necessary, referring to another professional

stem: A school psychologist is analyzing universal screening data for a school. Which of the following would be most useful for identifying students who may need Tier 2 support?
choiceA: Comparing students' scores to grade-level benchmarks
choiceB: Calculating the overall school average
choiceC: Reviewing only the scores of students already receiving special education
choiceD: Looking at last year's data only
correctText: Comparing students' scores to grade-level benchmarks

stem: Which of the following is a key principle of family-centered practice?
choiceA: Professionals make decisions about services without family input
choiceB: Families are viewed as partners in planning and decision-making
choiceC: Services focus exclusively on the child
choiceD: Communication with families is limited to formal meetings
correctText: Families are viewed as partners in planning and decision-making

stem: A school psychologist is interpreting data from a progress monitoring graph. The data show a flat trend line after four weeks of intervention. Which of the following is the most appropriate interpretation?
choiceA: The intervention is working well
choiceB: The student is making adequate progress
choiceC: The intervention may need to be modified or intensified
choiceD: The student should be referred for special education
correctText: The intervention may need to be modified or intensified

stem: Which of the following is most likely to be considered the best sign of successful implementation of a district-wide Tier 1 system of Positive Behavior Interventions and Supports (PBIS) that will lead to long-term benefits?
choiceA: The district recreation department posts signs indicating behavior expectations on each sports field.
choiceB: All schools use the same metrics for success and have consistent teaching strategies.
choiceC: Local businesses partner with the district to provide incentives for students.
choiceD: Students can recite the expectations of the program when asked.
correctText: All schools use the same metrics for success and have consistent teaching strategies.

stem: Dr. Shor receives paperwork for a new referral for Matthew, a tenth-grade student. Wanting to schedule a meeting to plan evaluations, Dr. Shor asks Matthew if it would be better to call his mother or his father. When Matthew responds that he has two fathers and that it would be fine to call either, Dr. Shor realizes he has made a mistake by assuming Matthew had two opposite-sex parents. Which of the following best describes Dr. Shor's assumption?
choiceA: An unbiased assumption
choiceB: An explicitly biased assumption
choiceC: An implicitly biased assumption
choiceD: Both an implicitly and explicitly biased assumption
correctText: An implicitly biased assumption

stem: A school psychologist is using behavioral consultation with a teacher to address a student's disruptive classroom behavior. What is the primary characteristic that makes this consultation 'behavioral'?
choiceA: It focuses on the student's observable behaviors and uses data collection
choiceB: It addresses the student's emotional and social needs
choiceC: It improves the teacher's instructional skills
choiceD: It involves both home and school settings
correctText: It focuses on the student's observable behaviors and uses data collection

stem: A school psychologist is consulting with a teacher who reports that a student seems withdrawn, has difficulty forming peer relationships, and appears anxious. The psychologist focuses on understanding the student's emotional experiences and social dynamics. This best represents which type of consultation?
choiceA: Behavioral consultation
choiceB: Mental health consultation
choiceC: Organizational consultation
choiceD: Conjoint behavioral consultation
correctText: Mental health consultation

stem: A school psychologist notices that a teacher consistently struggles with classroom management across multiple students. The psychologist works with the teacher to improve the teacher's skills and knowledge rather than focusing on individual student problems. This best describes which consultation model?
choiceA: Behavioral consultation
choiceB: Consultee-centered consultation
choiceC: Conjoint behavioral consultation
choiceD: Organizational consultation
correctText: Consultee-centered consultation

stem: A school psychologist facilitates meetings where both parents and teachers work together to address a student's behavior concerns, with interventions implemented in both home and school settings. This best describes which consultation model?
choiceA: Behavioral consultation
choiceB: Mental health consultation
choiceC: Conjoint behavioral consultation
choiceD: Consultee-centered consultation
correctText: Conjoint behavioral consultation

stem: A school psychologist works with the principal and leadership team to implement a school-wide positive behavior support system that affects all students and staff. This consultation is best described as:
choiceA: Behavioral consultation, because it addresses behavior
choiceB: Organizational consultation, because it addresses system-wide change
choiceC: Consultee-centered consultation, because it improves administrator skills
choiceD: Mental health consultation, because it affects school climate
correctText: Organizational consultation, because it addresses system-wide change

stem: A school psychologist is beginning consultation with a new teacher. The psychologist establishes mutual goals, clarifies roles and expectations, and builds rapport. This represents which stage of consultation?
choiceA: Problem identification
choiceB: Entry/Contracting
choiceC: Problem analysis
choiceD: Intervention implementation
correctText: Entry/Contracting

stem: During consultation, a school psychologist helps a teacher define a student's problem by collecting baseline data on how often the behavior occurs, when it occurs, and what it looks like. This activity best represents which stage of consultation?
choiceA: Entry/Contracting
choiceB: Problem identification
choiceC: Problem analysis
choiceD: Intervention evaluation
correctText: Problem identification

stem: A school psychologist analyzes collected data to identify patterns, hypothesizes why a behavior is occurring, and determines the function of the behavior. This represents which consultation stage?
choiceA: Problem identification
choiceB: Problem analysis
choiceC: Intervention implementation
choiceD: Evaluation
correctText: Problem analysis

stem: During the intervention stage of consultation, who is responsible for implementing the intervention with the student?
choiceA: The consultant (school psychologist), because they designed the intervention
choiceB: The consultee (teacher), because consultation is an indirect service
choiceC: Both the consultant and consultee together
choiceD: The student, with guidance from the consultant
correctText: The consultee (teacher), because consultation is an indirect service

stem: A school psychologist collects data after an intervention has been implemented to determine whether the student's behavior improved and whether the intervention should be continued, modified, or discontinued. This represents which stage of consultation?
choiceA: Problem analysis
choiceB: Intervention implementation
choiceC: Evaluation
choiceD: Entry/Contracting
correctText: Evaluation

stem: During a consultation meeting, a teacher expresses frustration about a student's behavior. The school psychologist responds by summarizing what the teacher said, reflecting the teacher's feelings, and asking clarifying questions. This demonstrates which consultation skill?
choiceA: Active listening
choiceB: Problem-solving
choiceC: Directive guidance
choiceD: Expert consultation
correctText: Active listening

stem: A teacher describes a complex situation with a student. The school psychologist responds, 'So if I understand correctly, you're saying that the behavior occurs primarily during transitions and when the student is asked to work independently. Is that accurate?' This response demonstrates:
choiceA: Giving expert advice
choiceB: Paraphrasing to clarify understanding
choiceC: Jumping to solutions
choiceD: Avoiding the problem
correctText: Paraphrasing to clarify understanding

stem: A teacher asks a school psychologist, 'What should I do about this student's behavior?' The psychologist responds by asking questions to help the teacher think through options rather than immediately providing solutions. This approach:
choiceA: Avoids the expert trap and promotes consultee ownership
choiceB: Shows the psychologist doesn't know the answer
choiceC: Wastes time when the psychologist could just provide the solution
choiceD: Is inappropriate because teachers expect expert advice
correctText: Avoids the expert trap and promotes consultee ownership

stem: A teacher is resistant to implementing a recommended intervention, saying 'I've tried everything and nothing works.' The most effective response from the school psychologist is to:
choiceA: Insist that the teacher try the recommended intervention
choiceB: Acknowledge the teacher's concerns, explore barriers, and collaboratively problem-solve
choiceC: Provide more research evidence supporting the intervention
choiceD: Take over and implement the intervention directly
correctText: Acknowledge the teacher's concerns, explore barriers, and collaboratively problem-solve

stem: A school psychologist is facilitating a meeting with teachers, parents, a community mental health provider, and a school administrator to coordinate services for a student. To effectively facilitate communication among these diverse stakeholders, the psychologist should:
choiceA: Ensure all parties understand each other's roles and perspectives
choiceB: Make decisions unilaterally to avoid conflict
choiceC: Focus only on the school's perspective
choiceD: Let each stakeholder speak without facilitation
correctText: Ensure all parties understand each other's roles and perspectives

stem: A school psychologist faces an ethical dilemma involving competing principles. According to NASP's ethical problem-solving model, what is the first step the psychologist should take?
choiceA: Identify the ethical principles in conflict
choiceB: Consult with a colleague or supervisor
choiceC: Determine the best course of action
choiceD: Document the decision-making process
correctText: Identify the ethical principles in conflict

stem: A student tells a school psychologist in confidence that they are planning to harm a classmate. The psychologist must balance confidentiality with the duty to protect. Which ethical principle takes precedence in this situation?
choiceA: Confidentiality, because the student trusted the psychologist
choiceB: Duty to protect, because there is an imminent threat to others
choiceC: Autonomy, because the student has the right to privacy
choiceD: Beneficence, because the psychologist should help the student
correctText: Duty to protect, because there is an imminent threat to others

stem: A school psychologist notices that a school administrator is pressuring teachers to delay special education referrals to reduce costs, which violates IDEA requirements. According to NASP ethical principles, what should the psychologist do first?
choiceA: Ignore the situation, as it is not the psychologist's responsibility
choiceB: Address the concern directly with the administrator and document the conversation
choiceC: Report the administrator to the state education department immediately
choiceD: Discuss the situation only with other psychologists
correctText: Address the concern directly with the administrator and document the conversation

stem: A school psychologist's close friend asks the psychologist to evaluate their child for special education services. The psychologist should:
choiceA: Proceed with the evaluation since they know the family well
choiceB: Decline the evaluation and refer to another qualified professional
choiceC: Conduct the evaluation but charge a reduced fee
choiceD: Proceed only if the friend signs a waiver
correctText: Decline the evaluation and refer to another qualified professional

stem: A school psychologist is asked to conduct a neuropsychological evaluation, which requires specialized training the psychologist does not have. The most ethical response is to:
choiceA: Attempt the evaluation using general assessment knowledge
choiceB: Decline and refer to a qualified neuropsychologist
choiceC: Conduct a basic evaluation and note limitations in the report
choiceD: Accept but request additional time to learn the procedures
correctText: Decline and refer to a qualified neuropsychologist

stem: A student has a medical condition that substantially limits a major life activity but does not require specialized instruction. Under which law would this student most likely be eligible for services?
choiceA: IDEA, because it covers all disabilities
choiceB: Section 504, because it covers students who need accommodations but not specialized instruction
choiceC: Both IDEA and Section 504 equally
choiceD: Neither, because specialized instruction is required
correctText: Section 504, because it covers students who need accommodations but not specialized instruction

stem: What is the key difference in the services provided under IDEA versus Section 504?
choiceA: IDEA provides accommodations; Section 504 provides specialized instruction
choiceB: IDEA provides specialized instruction and related services; Section 504 provides accommodations and modifications for access
choiceC: There is no difference in services provided
choiceD: IDEA is for physical disabilities; Section 504 is for learning disabilities
correctText: IDEA provides specialized instruction and related services; Section 504 provides accommodations and modifications for access

stem: How do evaluation requirements differ between IDEA and Section 504?
choiceA: IDEA requires comprehensive evaluation by a multidisciplinary team; Section 504 requires evaluation by a team of knowledgeable persons
choiceB: Section 504 requires more comprehensive evaluation than IDEA
choiceC: Both require identical evaluation procedures
choiceD: Neither requires formal evaluation
