correctText: IDEA requires comprehensive evaluation by a multidisciplinary team; Section 504 requires evaluation by a team of knowledgeable persons

stem: Under FERPA, which of the following parties can access a student's educational records without parental consent?
choiceA: Any school employee who requests access
choiceB: School officials with legitimate educational interests
choiceC: Other parents in the school
choiceD: Community members conducting research
correctText: School officials with legitimate educational interests

stem: A parent believes that information in their child's educational record is inaccurate. Under FERPA, what right does the parent have?
choiceA: The parent has no right to challenge the information
choiceB: The parent can request amendment, and if the school refuses, the parent can request a hearing
choiceC: The parent can demand immediate removal of the information
choiceD: The parent must file a lawsuit to correct the record
correctText: The parent can request amendment, and if the school refuses, the parent can request a hearing

stem: According to the Rowley case, what must an IEP provide to meet the FAPE standard under IDEA?
choiceA: The maximum potential of the student
choiceB: Some educational benefit, not necessarily the best possible education
choiceC: Equal outcomes compared to non-disabled peers
choiceD: Services that maximize the student's potential
correctText: Some educational benefit, not necessarily the best possible education

stem: How did the Endrew F. v. Douglas County School District case modify the Rowley standard for FAPE?
choiceA: It lowered the standard to require only minimal benefit
choiceB: It raised the standard to require meaningful educational benefit, not just 'some benefit'
choiceC: It eliminated the FAPE requirement entirely
choiceD: It applied only to students with severe disabilities
correctText: It raised the standard to require meaningful educational benefit, not just 'some benefit'

stem: The Larry P. v. Riles case prohibited the use of IQ tests for what purpose in California?
choiceA: Identifying gifted students
choiceB: Placing African American students in special education programs for educable mentally retarded
choiceC: Determining eligibility for all special education services
choiceD: Assessing academic achievement
correctText: Placing African American students in special education programs for educable mentally retarded

stem: According to the Tarasoff case, when does a school psychologist have a duty to warn or protect?
choiceA: Whenever a student mentions any negative feelings
choiceB: When a student makes a specific, credible threat of serious harm to an identifiable victim
choiceC: Only after a student has already harmed someone
choiceD: When parents request information about their child
correctText: When a student makes a specific, credible threat of serious harm to an identifiable victim

stem: A school psychologist learns that a student has made a specific threat to harm a classmate. Based on relevant case law, the psychologist should:
choiceA: Maintain confidentiality and not disclose the threat
choiceB: Warn the intended victim and/or take reasonable steps to protect them, even if it means breaching confidentiality
choiceC: Wait to see if the student follows through with the threat
choiceD: Only report if the student has a history of violence
correctText: Warn the intended victim and/or take reasonable steps to protect them, even if it means breaching confidentiality

stem: A student with a disability is being considered for a disciplinary removal that would result in more than 10 consecutive school days out of school. What must occur before this removal can be implemented?
choiceA: Nothing - the removal can proceed immediately
choiceB: A manifestation determination review must be conducted
choiceC: The student's IEP must be revised
choiceD: Parent consent must be obtained
correctText: A manifestation determination review must be conducted

stem: During a manifestation determination review, the team must answer which of the following questions?
choiceA: Was the behavior wrong and should the student be punished?
choiceB: Was the conduct caused by or did it have a direct relationship to the student's disability, and was the conduct a direct result of the school's failure to implement the IEP?
choiceC: Does the student have a disability?
choiceD: Should the student be placed in a more restrictive setting?
correctText: Was the conduct caused by or did it have a direct relationship to the student's disability, and was the conduct a direct result of the school's failure to implement the IEP?

stem: Before conducting an initial evaluation for special education, what must the school psychologist explain to parents to obtain informed consent?
choiceA: Only that an evaluation will be conducted
choiceB: The purpose of the evaluation, procedures to be used, and that consent can be revoked
choiceC: The results of the evaluation before it is conducted
choiceD: That consent is optional and not required
correctText: The purpose of the evaluation, procedures to be used, and that consent can be revoked

stem: The Least Restrictive Environment (LRE) requirement under IDEA means that students with disabilities should be educated:
choiceA: Always in general education classrooms
choiceB: With non-disabled peers to the maximum extent appropriate
choiceC: In separate special education schools
choiceD: Wherever is most convenient for the school
correctText: With non-disabled peers to the maximum extent appropriate

stem: Under IDEA and professional standards, when is the use of seclusion or restraint with a student with a disability allowed?
choiceA: As a routine behavior management strategy
choiceB: Only when there is an imminent danger of serious physical harm to the student or others
choiceC: Whenever the student is disruptive
choiceD: When parents request it as a consequence
correctText: Only when there is an imminent danger of serious physical harm to the student or others

stem: A school psychologist has been asked to evaluate a third-grade student for a possible learning disability. The student's family reports that the native language at home is Portuguese and that the student is in the process of acquiring English. Best practice dictates that the minimum standard for classification is a discrepancy between general intellectual functioning and full-scale achievement found via assessment
choiceA: in the student's native language only
choiceB: in English only
choiceC: in both the student's native language and in English
choiceD: using standardized nonverbal tests
correctText: in both the student's native language and in English

stem: Which of the following is a Tier 1 preventive strategy?
choiceA: Behaviorally focused parent-management training
choiceB: Environmentally designed crime deterrence
choiceC: Conflict de-escalation
choiceD: Student check-in/check-out meetings
correctText: Environmentally designed crime deterrence

stem: Which of the following best describes how a school psychologist can measure interfering behaviors during a functional behavioral assessment?
choiceA: The school psychologist receives documentation of the number of discipline referrals and in-school suspensions a student received.
choiceB: The school psychologist assumes that variables that are present during the observation of a problem behavior were also present during previous instances of the behavior.
choiceC: The school psychologist observes a student committing a problem behavior during reading instruction and assumes that reading instruction triggers the behavior.
choiceD: The school psychologist converts the number of physical fights recorded over a two-month period to the average number of fights per week.
correctText: The school psychologist converts the number of physical fights recorded over a two-month period to the average number of fights per week.

stem: In which TWO of the following situations is a school psychologist's request to obtain a student's medical record with parent authorization most appropriate?
choiceA: The student reports fatigue and irritability that is not clearly related to a health condition.
choiceB: The student is newly enrolled in the school after moving to the district from out of state.
choiceC: The student's classroom teacher notes that the student goes to the school clinic for medication twice during the school day.
choiceD: The school psychologist has a personal interest in studying the etiology of autism spectrum disorder (ASD) and is examining the records of students who are receiving services for ASD.
correctText: The student reports fatigue and irritability that is not clearly related to a health condition. | The student's classroom teacher notes that the student goes to the school clinic for medication twice during the school day.

stem: Lenny is a fifth-grade student who receives individual counseling as a related service to address poor frustration tolerance for challenging academic tasks and verbal and physical aggression when he is upset. His primary counseling goal is to identify and apply anger management strategies that are more appropriate and effective. Using a cognitive-behavioral approach, the school psychologist is most likely to do which of the following?
choiceA: Determine effective reinforcers to reward Lenny when he engages in alternatives to the target behaviors.
choiceB: Discuss the choices Lenny is making with him and help him to identify what he can do differently to get what he wants.
choiceC: Help Lenny identify the distortions in thinking that affect how he responds to challenging academic tasks.
choiceD: Describe Lenny's behaviors and reflect his feelings while he plays with toys or other available materials of his choosing.
correctText: Help Lenny identify the distortions in thinking that affect how he responds to challenging academic tasks.

stem: According to NASP, which of the following is an evidence-based framework for effectively integrating multiple systems and services to simultaneously address students' academic achievement, behavior, and social-emotional well-being?
choiceA: Positive behavioral interventions and supports (PBIS)
choiceB: Multitiered system of support (MTSS)
choiceC: Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA)
choiceD: Bully proofing your school (BPYS)
correctText: Multitiered system of support (MTSS)

stem: Viraag, a third-grade student, was referred by his teacher to the school psychologist due to concerns about his ability to perform expected grade-level math tasks. Which of the following statements best reflects the school psychologist's first step in addressing the concern?
choiceA: The school psychologist identifies a high-achieving student in the class who can serve as a peer tutor for Viraag.
choiceB: The school psychologist asks the teacher to identify the typical math performance of a different student in the class who performs at grade level.
choiceC: The school psychologist obtains permission to assess Viraag with an individually administered math diagnostic achievement test.
choiceD: The school psychologist selects a math-skills worksheet that can be administered to the entire class and that represents skills that the average student should successfully complete.
correctText: The school psychologist selects a math-skills worksheet that can be administered to the entire class and that represents skills that the average student should successfully complete.

stem: Which of the following is the most accurate definition of primary intervention?
choiceA: Primary intervention is designed to meet the needs of most students within the school and is applied across all settings.
choiceB: Primary intervention addresses the needs of students who require additional assistance to prevent academic or social difficulties.
choiceC: Primary intervention is essential for students who present with significant risk factors and may require more specialized forms of assistance beyond the support provided in general education.
choiceD: Primary intervention is individualized to best meet the needs of students who require more specialized forms of assistance beyond the support provided in general education.
correctText: Primary intervention is designed to meet the needs of most students within the school and is applied across all settings.

stem: Which of the following best describes how a school psychologist might assess social influences on a student's development of a mental health issue?
choiceA: Meeting with the parents to discuss the family's history of diagnosed mental health issues
choiceB: Asking the parents for the student's medical history
choiceC: Interviewing the teacher and parents about the student's peer relationships and reactions to success and failure
choiceD: Completing a social history to determine whether the student met all developmental milestones, within normal limits
correctText: Interviewing the teacher and parents about the student's peer relationships and reactions to success and failure

stem: Which federal law specifically allows parents to choose to receive procedural safeguards electronically?
choiceA: Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA)
choiceB: Protection of Pupil Rights Amendment (PPRA)
choiceC: Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA)
choiceD: Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA)
correctText: Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA)

stem: Which TWO of the following best describe secondary-level interventions when utilizing a positive behavior support model?
choiceA: The inclusion of counseling in a student's IEP to address defiant behaviors
choiceB: Classroom lessons on positive character development
choiceC: Schoolwide assemblies promoting good behavior and celebrating schoolwide success at following rules
choiceD: A classwide behavior plan where all students can earn prizes for their behavior
correctText: Classroom lessons on positive character development | A classwide behavior plan where all students can earn prizes for their behavior

stem: A school psychologist notices that Yusuf, a tenth-grade student, has stopped eating lunch, quit the soccer team, and is increasingly irritable with his friends. He has also become more withdrawn. Which of the following mental health concerns is Yusuf most likely experiencing?
choiceA: Anxiety
choiceB: Depression
choiceC: Bipolar disorder
choiceD: Conduct disorder
correctText: Depression

stem: A school psychologist implements a new aggression-reduction program with several second-grade students and plans to monitor the students for the next three years. The school psychologist finds that relative to the start of the program, aggression in the group of students who received the intervention is down 35 percent. Based on these results, which of the following threats to internal validity has the school psychologist most likely failed to account for?
choiceA: Instrumentation
choiceB: Maturation
choiceC: Attrition
choiceD: History
correctText: Maturation

stem: Mr. Suzuki, a school psychologist, is asked to administer an assessment with which he has no experience. Before using the assessment with students, Mr. Suzuki completes a continuing education module on the assessment and asks for supervision and consultation from another school psychologist in the district who has used the assessment before. Mr. Suzuki is acting in accordance with of the following NASP Principles for Professional Ethics?
choiceA: Autonomy and self-determination
choiceB: Competence
choiceC: Fairness, equity, and justice
choiceD: Honesty and integrity in professional relationships
correctText: Competence

stem: In which of the following scenarios would it be appropriate for a school psychologist to break confidentiality?
choiceA: A high school student informs the school psychologist that they are sexually active with a same-age partner.
choiceB: A student tells the school psychologist that they intend to harm another student.
choiceC: A student tells the school psychologist that there are firearms in their home.
choiceD: A student tells the school psychologist that they cheated on an exam.
correctText: A student tells the school psychologist that they intend to harm another student.

stem: While selecting a test to use in school, a school psychologist discovered that a particular test was not very consistent or stable over time. In other words, some test takers' scores varied each time they took it. The school psychologist can most likely conclude which of the following?
choiceA: The test is biased.
choiceB: The test has poor evidence of validity.
choiceC: The test makers did not use an appropriate norming sample.
choiceD: The test is not reliable.
correctText: The test is not reliable.

stem: Claire is a second-grade student who experiences difficulty following her parents' directions at home. When her parents meet with the school psychologist, they ask for advice on how to improve Claire's behaviors at home. Claire's parents shared that they have used consequences in the past such as taking away privileges, giving Claire additional chores to complete, and implementing an early bedtime. Which of the following should the school psychologist suggest Claire's parents try instead?
choiceA: Focusing on using one type of punishment procedure instead of several different approaches
choiceB: Increasing the duration of the consequences, such as taking away privileges for three days instead of one
choiceC: Removing consequences for rule-breaking behavior
choiceD: Clearly stating the house rules Claire is expected to follow and using positive reinforcement for her compliance with the rules
correctText: Clearly stating the house rules Claire is expected to follow and using positive reinforcement for her compliance with the rules

stem: Ms. Trainor is frustrated with her student, Hamilton. Hamilton has an Individualized Education Program (IEP), but he has multiple severe disabilities, and he makes very little progress in school because of the severity of his disabilities. Ms. Trainor tells the school psychologist that she does not believe that Hamilton is benefiting from attending school. The school psychologist politely tells Ms. Trainor that Hamilton has a right to an education, no matter how severe his disabilities. The school psychologist's response best illustrates which of the following?
choiceA: Zero-reject principle
choiceB: Child Find
choiceC: Least restrictive environment
choiceD: Nondiscriminatory evaluation
correctText: Zero-reject principle

stem: A school psychologist would like to evaluate the effectiveness of a school's Positive Behavioral Interventions and Supports (PBIS) initiative. E-mailing teachers to remind them about certain classroom expectations can serve as a means of
choiceA: treatment fidelity
choiceB: progress monitoring
choiceC: intervention development
choiceD: universal screening
correctText: treatment fidelity

stem: A student's score on a reading comprehension test is in the 80th percentile. Which of the following best explains the student's score?
choiceA: The student scored higher than 20 percent of all the students who took the test.
choiceB: The student earned 80 percent correct on the test.
choiceC: The student scored 80 out of 100 questions correct on the test.
choiceD: The student scored higher than 80 percent of all the students who took the test.
correctText: The student scored higher than 80 percent of all the students who took the test.

stem: A school psychologist in an elementary school reads a study about a counseling technique that helps with behavior management. The study took place in a summer-camp setting and indicated this technique was associated with reduced aggression. The school psychologist is interested in using the technique at the school but is concerned about whether that summer-camp setting would generalize to an elementary school classroom. The school psychologist is primarily concerned about which of the following?
choiceA: Test-retest reliability
choiceB: Internal validity
choiceC: Content validity
choiceD: Ecological validity
correctText: Ecological validity

stem: Which TWO of the following accurately describe a school psychologist's legal and ethical responsibility as an advocate for children and their families?
choiceA: Identifying and working to change school practices that may unintentionally discriminate against or result in harm to transgender students
choiceB: Clearly indicating when they are giving their opinion as a private citizen versus as a public employee during a public meeting regarding a controversial school policy
choiceC: Demonstrating respect for diversity by adopting a color-blind perspective toward students of color
choiceD: Incorporating their personal and religious beliefs in advice given to students if these beliefs do not conflict with the law
correctText: Identifying and working to change school practices that may unintentionally discriminate against or result in harm to transgender students | Clearly indicating when they are giving their opinion as a private citizen versus as a public employee during a public meeting regarding a controversial school policy

stem: A classroom teacher wants to refer a student for evaluation for a learning disability. The student emigrated to the United States two and a half years ago, quickly learned English, and can communicate fluently with all the children in the classroom. However, the student continues to have difficulty with schoolwork, frequently asks for directions to be repeated, and demonstrates poor comprehension based on written work. To help the teacher understand the student's difficulty, it is most important that the school psychologist explain which of the following?
choiceA: The difference between acculturation and assimilation
choiceB: The difference between basic interpersonal communication skills (BICS) and cognitive academic language proficiency (CALP)
choiceC: The Culture-Language Interpretive Matrix (C-LIM)
choiceD: The cultural and linguistic biases that are present in testing
correctText: The difference between basic interpersonal communication skills (BICS) and cognitive academic language proficiency (CALP)

stem: Evidence-based practice (EBP) is a movement that has gained much attention in the field of school psychology. Some EBPs have been found to have empirical support in addressing the problems associated with common mental health and social-emotional needs of students. Which of the following is a supported EBP?
choiceA: Student suspension to address conduct problems
choiceB: Cognitive behavioral therapy for the treatment of internalizing problems
choiceC: Student retention to address immaturity
choiceD: Diet modifications for the treatment of autism spectrum disorders
correctText: Cognitive behavioral therapy for the treatment of internalizing problems

stem: A test has a mean score of 100 and a standard deviation of 15. A student receives a standard score of 85. The student's z score would be

A school psychologist evaluates a child's ability to attend to information, hold information in immediate awareness, concentrate, and perform a mental operation. Which of the following is the school psychologist measuring?
choiceA: Verbal comprehension
choiceB: Working memory
choiceC: Processing speed
choiceD: Fluid reasoning
correctText: Working memory

stem: Joel is a fourth-grade student who has been referred for a special education evaluation. The results of the evaluation show that he is functioning below grade level in reading comprehension. Additionally, Joel's teacher and parent report that he has significant difficulty coping with setbacks and often has emotional outbursts when overwhelmed. The student support team recommends that Joel be classified under the category of Specific Learning Disability. Based on this information, which TWO of the following will most likely appear in Joel's IEP?
choiceA: Small-group counseling
choiceB: Social work services
choiceC: Modification of reading assignments
choiceD: Individual instruction in reading
correctText: Small-group counseling | Individual instruction in reading

stem: A high school sophomore asks to meet with the school psychologist for counseling but only under the condition that the school psychologist does not inform the student's parents. Which of the following is the best course of action for the school psychologist to take?
choiceA: Informing the student's parents of this request in order to gain parental consent despite the student's wishes
choiceB: Ensuring that the student is not in danger and informing the student that parental consent is required for ongoing counseling
choiceC: Providing counseling to the student without parental consent since the student is in high school
choiceD: Informing the student that counseling cannot be provided without parental consent and sending the student back to class
correctText: Ensuring that the student is not in danger and informing the student that parental consent is required for ongoing counseling

stem: Interagency collaboration for students with disabilities is most useful for doing which of the following tasks?
choiceA: Developing IEPs
choiceB: Implementing disciplinary programs
choiceC: Increasing high school enrollment
choiceD: Planning for postsecondary transitions
correctText: Planning for postsecondary transitions

stem: Ms. Carey is a school psychologist at a middle school. Within the first six weeks of the school year, there has been a notable increase in behaviors related to fighting, name-calling, and general student disagreements. Each time a student is referred to the office for a disciplinary problem, the office contacts Ms. Carey to provide counseling services. Which of the following might Ms. Carey suggest in a meeting with school staff as the next best response to this increase in general need?
choiceA: Providing intensive behavioral interventions and supports for each student referred for disciplinary problems
choiceB: Implementing schoolwide positive behavioral intervention and supports (SWPBIS) and social-emotional learning
choiceC: Allowing other school staff to assist in meeting with students with problem behaviors
choiceD: Providing more small-group instruction in conflict resolution and general social skills to all students
correctText: Implementing schoolwide positive behavioral intervention and supports (SWPBIS) and social-emotional learning

stem: A school psychologist is working with a family from a diverse cultural background who seems resistant to intervention recommendations. What is the most effective strategy?
choiceA: Provide less than the required supervision hours
choiceB: Intervention before assessment
choiceC: Build trust by understanding family values and adapting communication styles
choiceD: Provide direct instruction only
correctText: Build trust by understanding family values and adapting communication styles

stem: A school psychologist is working with a family from a diverse cultural background who wants to collaborate on an intervention plan. What is the most effective strategy?
choiceA: Make a recommendation based on teacher observations alone
choiceB: Involve the family as partners, recognize their strengths, and promote home-school collaboration
choiceC: Cognitive Behavioral Therapy
choiceD: Include students with severe conduct disorders in group counseling
correctText: Involve the family as partners, recognize their strengths, and promote home-school collaboration

stem: A school psychologist needs to coordinate services for a student who needs multiple community services. What is the most appropriate approach for working with community agencies?
choiceA: Apply adult diagnostic criteria directly to children
choiceB: Coordinate services by understanding agency roles, facilitating communication between systems, and ensuring seamless service delivery
choiceC: A replacement behavior that serves a different function
choiceD: Determine appropriate punishment for the behavior
correctText: Coordinate services by understanding agency roles, facilitating communication between systems, and ensuring seamless service delivery

stem: A student with a sensory impairment needs a reduced assignment load. This is an example of:
choiceA: A replacement behavior that serves a different function
choiceB: Make a recommendation based on teacher observations alone
choiceC: A modification (changes what the student learns)
choiceD: Investigate the abuse allegations before reporting
correctText: A modification (changes what the student learns)

stem: A student's academic progress is influenced by classroom factors. Which factor is most likely to impact achievement?
choiceA: Classroom climate
choiceB: Apply adult diagnostic criteria directly to children
choiceC: Investigate the abuse allegations before reporting
choiceD: Classroom climate and teacher-student relationships
correctText: Classroom climate and teacher-student relationships

stem: A student's academic performance is affected by developmental readiness. Which consideration is most important?
choiceA: Apply the rule absolutely without considering context
choiceB: Cognitive development
choiceC: Make disciplinary decisions about the student
choiceD: Cognitive development and readiness for academic tasks
correctText: Cognitive development and readiness for academic tasks

stem: A student's academic performance is affected by cultural background. Which consideration is most important?
choiceA: Cultural learning styles, values, and communication patterns
choiceB: Determine appropriate punishment for the behavior
choiceC: Data collection always comes before intervention
choiceD: Allow full copying and release of test protocols
correctText: Cultural learning styles, values, and communication patterns

stem: A school psychologist is planning an intervention for a elementary school student who experiences anxiety. Which approach is most developmentally appropriate?
choiceA: Concrete, play-based, visual strategies with shorter sessions
choiceB: Breach confidentiality for general concerns about student well-being
choiceC: Allow full copying and release of test protocols
choiceD: Implement an intervention without reviewing assessment data
correctText: Concrete, play-based, visual strategies with shorter sessions

stem: A school psychologist is planning an intervention for a elementary school student who struggles with social skills. Which approach is most developmentally appropriate?
choiceA: Concrete, play-based, visual strategies with shorter sessions
choiceB: Provide the best possible education
choiceC: Use progress monitoring tools for program evaluation
choiceD: Concrete
correctText: Concrete, play-based, visual strategies with shorter sessions

stem: A student experiencing anxiety is likely to show which impact on academic performance?
choiceA: Intervention before assessment
choiceB: Investigate the abuse allegations before reporting
choiceC: Impact on academic performance, engagement, and learning
choiceD: Impact on academic performance
correctText: Impact on academic performance, engagement, and learning

stem: A student experiencing trauma is likely to show which impact on academic performance?
choiceA: Provide the best possible education
choiceB: Breach confidentiality for general concerns about student well-being
choiceC: Impact on academic performance, engagement, and learning
choiceD: Make a medical diagnosis
correctText: Impact on academic performance, engagement, and learning

stem: A school psychologist is working with a family from a collectivist culture who expresses concerns about the school's approach. What is the most effective strategy?
choiceA: Allow full copying and release of test protocols
choiceB: Recommend services without analyzing progress monitoring data
choiceC: Use an individual assessment for universal screening
choiceD: Build trust by understanding family values and adapting communication styles
correctText: Build trust by understanding family values and adapting communication styles

stem: A school psychologist is working with a family from a collectivist culture who has difficulty attending meetings. What is the most effective strategy?
choiceA: Deny access to records without legal basis
choiceB: Investigate the abuse allegations before reporting
choiceC: Identify and address barriers to engagement, such as scheduling or transportation
choiceD: Use progress monitoring tools for program evaluation
correctText: Identify and address barriers to engagement, such as scheduling or transportation

stem: A school psychologist needs to coordinate services for a student who needs vocational support. What is the most appropriate approach for working with community agencies?
choiceA: A replacement behavior that serves a different function
choiceB: Attention
choiceC: Coordinate services by understanding agency roles, facilitating communication between systems, and ensuring seamless service delivery
choiceD: Use progress monitoring tools for program evaluation
correctText: Coordinate services by understanding agency roles, facilitating communication between systems, and ensuring seamless service delivery

stem: A student with ADHD needs assistive technology for writing. This is an example of:
choiceA: An accommodation (changes how the student accesses the curriculum)
choiceB: Diagnose the student with a medical condition
choiceC: Students only need comprehensive evaluations before intervention
choiceD: Use a diagnostic assessment for weekly monitoring
correctText: An accommodation (changes how the student accesses the curriculum)

stem: A student with ADHD needs a reduced assignment load. This is an example of:
choiceA: A modification (changes what the student learns)
choiceB: Provide direct instruction in reading
choiceC: Breach confidentiality for general concerns about student well-being
choiceD: Use progress monitoring tools for program evaluation
correctText: A modification (changes what the student learns)

stem: A student with a physical disability needs extended time on tests. This is an example of:
choiceA: Use an individual assessment for universal screening
choiceB: Attention
choiceC: An accommodation (changes how the student accesses the curriculum)
choiceD: Investigate the abuse allegations before reporting
correctText: An accommodation (changes how the student accesses the curriculum)

stem: A student's academic progress is influenced by socioeconomic factors. Which factor is most likely to impact achievement?
choiceA: Breach confidentiality for general concerns ab...
choiceB: Use a diagnostic assessment for weekly monitoring
choiceC: Access to resources and stability
choiceD: Provide direct instruction only
correctText: Access to resources and stability

stem: A student's academic performance is affected by social relationships. Which consideration is most important?
choiceA: Peer relationships and family structure
choiceB: Provide less than the required supervision hours
choiceC: Use progress monitoring tools for program evaluation
choiceD: Include students with severe conduct disorders in group...
correctText: Peer relationships and family structure

stem: A student's academic performance is affected by multiple interacting factors. Which consideration is most important?
choiceA: The interaction of biological, cultural, and social factors
choiceB: The interaction of biological
choiceC: Use an individual assessment for universal screening
choiceD: Apply the rule absolutely without considering context
correctText: The interaction of biological, cultural, and social factors

stem: A school psychologist is planning an intervention for a high school student who has behavioral challenges. Which approach is most developmentally appropriate?
choiceA: Abstract, discussion-based approaches with longer sessions and peer-focused activities
choiceB: Use curriculum-based measurement for comprehensive evaluation
choiceC: Schedule assessment for next week
choiceD: Include students with severe conduct disorders in group counseling
correctText: Abstract, discussion-based approaches with longer sessions and peer-focused activities

stem: A student experiencing ADHD is likely to show which impact on school engagement?
choiceA: Use curriculum-based measurement for comprehensive evaluation
choiceB: Impact on academic performance, engagement, and learning
choiceC: Make a recommendation based on teacher observations alone
choiceD: Provide direct instruction only
correctText: Impact on academic performance, engagement, and learning

stem: A student experiencing ADHD is likely to show which impact on test-taking?
choiceA: Assign homework to the student
choiceB: Impact on academic performance, engagement, and learning
choiceC: Use a diagnostic assessment for weekly monitoring
choiceD: Prescribe treatment without proper authorization
correctText: Impact on academic performance, engagement, and learning

stem: Interagency collaboration for students with disabilities is most useful for:
choiceA: Planning for postsecondary transitions and connecting students to employment and education opportunities
choiceB: Schedule assessment for next week
choiceC: Intervention before assessment
choiceD: Use a screening tool to determine eligibility
correctText: Planning for postsecondary transitions and connecting students to employment and education opportunities

stem: A school psychologist is working with parents to address homework completion at home. What is the most effective approach?
choiceA: Schedule assessment for next week
choiceB: Use curriculum-based measurement for comprehensive evaluation
choiceC: Teach parents behavior management strategies including positive reinforcement, clear rules, and consistent consequences
choiceD: Disclose confidential information to unauthorized personnel
correctText: Teach parents behavior management strategies including positive reinforcement, clear rules, and consistent consequences

stem: Before conducting an assessment, a school psychologist should:
choiceA: Review background information including student records, medical records, previous interventions, and developmental history
choiceB: Determine appropriate punishment for the behavior
choiceC: Implement an intervention program
choiceD: Implement an intervention without reviewing assessment data
correctText: Review background information including student records, medical records, previous interventions, and developmental history

stem: A problem-solving framework (MTSS/RTI) should be used as the basis for:
choiceA: Apply the rule absolutely without considering context
choiceB: Use progress monitoring tools for program evaluation
choiceC: All professional activities including assessment, intervention, and decision-making
choiceD: Investigate the abuse allegations before reporting
correctText: All professional activities including assessment, intervention, and decision-making

stem: When assessing a student with multiple severe disabilities, the school psychologist should:
choiceA: Use a diagnostic assessment for weekly monitoring
choiceB: Adapt assessment procedures, consider medical factors, involve specialists, and use appropriate accommodations
choiceC: Provide direct instruction only
choiceD: The intervention caused the improvement because it was followed by better scores
correctText: Adapt assessment procedures, consider medical factors, involve specialists, and use appropriate accommodations

stem: To ensure fidelity of implementation for a school-wide program, a school psychologist should:
choiceA: Use an individual assessment for universal screening
choiceB: Cognitive Behavioral Therapy
choiceC: Provide training, coaching, reminders, and ongoing monitoring to ensure consistent implementation
choiceD: Schedule assessment for next week
correctText: Provide training, coaching, reminders, and ongoing monitoring to ensure consistent implementation

stem: A school psychologist wants to evaluate the effectiveness of a reading intervention program. What is the most comprehensive approach?
choiceA: Use curriculum-based measurement for comprehensive evaluation
choiceB: Allow full copying and release of test protocols
choiceC: Data collection never comes before intervention
choiceD: Collect outcome data, process data, stakeholder feedback, and compare to baseline or control groups
correctText: Collect outcome data, process data, stakeholder feedback, and compare to baseline or control groups

stem: To maintain professional competence, a school psychologist should:
choiceA: Provide direct instruction only
choiceB: Use an individual assessment for universal screening
